 Grave, Grave, North Brabant, The Netherlands":"Grave, Noord-Brabant, Nederlandene"},"nl":{"ca 1314–between 1369 and 1370":"1314–van 1369 to 1370","1312–1356":"1312–1356","1333–1391":"1333–1391","1314–1370":"1314–1370","1314":"1314","1356":"1356","1312":"1312","1333":"1333","about 17 August 1356":"circa 17 augustus 1356","1370":"1370","1391":"1391","between 1369 and 1370":"van 1369 to 1370","ca 1314":"1314","Noord-Brabant, Nederland":"Noord-Brabant, Nederland","North Brabant, Netherlands":"Noord-Brabant, Nederland","Kasteel Grave, Grave, North Brabant, The Netherlands":"Grave, Noord-Brabant, Nederland"},"en":{"ca 1314–between 1369 and 1370":"1314–from 1369 to 1370","1312–1356":"1312–1356","1333–1391":"1333–1391","1314–1370":"1314–1370","1314":"1314","1356":"1356","1312":"1312","1333":"1333","about 17 August 1356":"about 17 August 1356","1370":"1370","1391":"1391","between 1369 and 1370":"from 1369 to 1370","ca 1314":"1314","Noord-Brabant, Nederland":"North Brabant, Netherlands","North Brabant, Netherlands":"North Brabant, Netherlands","Kasteel Grave, Grave, North Brabant, The Netherlands":"Grave, North Brabant, Netherlands","nameMeanings":[{"name":"van","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Anh, Thanh, Hung, Minh, Vinh, Dung, Hue, Huong, Lan, Quang, Tan, Thuy, Hong, Chi, Hang, Ho, Pok, Sang, Bai, Chin, Ching, Chu, Chuan, Dong.","Vietnamese (<b>Vạn</b>): from the Chinese surname 萬, see   Wan   1.","Vietnamese (<b>Văn</b>): from the Chinese surnames 文 or 聞, see   Wen   2 and 3, and also 5 below."],"variants":[{"name":"Wan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Hong, Yi, Qi, Qiang, Wai, Yiu, Yuk, Chien-Min, Fang, Hin, Jichun, Li, Man, Chung, Min, Yiping, Pak, Sik, Sung Man.  Vietnamese Tin, Bang, Da, Hien, Hoi, Lan, Minh Quang, Sau, Tich, Tung, Yaping, Yuet.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 萬, which means ‘ten thousand’ literally or ‘very great number’ figuratively: (i) from the personal name of Bi Wan (畢萬), an official in the state of Jin (located in present-day Shanxi province). He was said to be a descendant of Bi Gong Gao (known as Duke of Bi), the 15th son of the virtuous King Wen of Zhou (reined 1152–1056  BC ). Bi Wan was later granted the fiefdom of Wei (魏), which in 403  BC  became the state of Wei (located in present-day Shanxi, Shaanxi, Henan and Hebei provinces). Some of his descendants adopted Wei (魏) as their surname, while others inherited 萬 (Wan), his personal name, as their surname. (ii) from the personal name Wan (萬), style name of Rui Bo (芮伯, the Earl of Rui), an official of the Western Zhou dynasty (1046–771  BC ), who was granted the fief Rui (located in Ruicheng in Shaanxi province). Some of his descendants inherited Rui (芮), the name of the fief, as their surname, while others inherited 萬 (Wan), his style name, as their surname. (iii) from the placename Wan (萬), the name of a fief (located in Juxian in Shandong province) granted during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ) to an official in the ancient state of Chu. (iv) from the first element of the name of the Wan Si (萬俟) family, who lived in the downstream areas of the Yellow River during the Northern Qi dynasty (550–577  AD ). (v) from the second element of the name of the Tu Wan (吐萬) family, who are members of the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 完, meaning ‘complete’ in Chinese: (i) said to be borne by the descendants of Huan Zhui, a grandson of the Duke Huan of Song (ruler of the state of Song, died 651  BC ). (ii) from Wan (完), the name of Qu Wan (屈完), an official in the state of Chu during the Spring and Autumn Period (770–476  BC ). (iii) shortened form of the compound surname Wan-Yan (完顔), a surname from minority ethnic groups such as Juchen ethnic group in ancient northern China."]}]},{"name":"Mieren","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Fritz, Konrad.","German and Dutch: patronymic from   Mies   2."],"variants":[{"name":"Mies","meanings":["South German: topographic name for someone who lived by a bog, Middle High German <i>mies</i>; or a habitational name from Mies, a place called with the same word.","Dutch and Flemish: from a short form of the personal name <i>Bartholomeus</i> (see   Bartholomew  ) or   Michael  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Lijsbeth van Mieren was born in 1314, in North Brabant, Netherlands. She had at least 1 daughter with Heer Jan Van Wijtfliet van Blaasveld en Cuijk. She died from 1369 to 1370."},"et":{"ca 1314–between 1369 and 1370":"1314–1369 kuni 1370","1312–1356":"1312–1356","1333–1391":"1333–1391","1314–1370":"1314–1370","1314":"1314","1356":"1356","1312":"1312","1333":"1333","about 17 August 1356":"umbes 17. august 1356","1370":"1370","1391":"1391","between 1369 and 1370":"1369 kuni 1370","ca 1314":"1314","Noord-Brabant, Nederland":"Noord-Brabant, Madalmaad","North Brabant, Netherlands":"Noord-Brabant, Madalmaad","Kasteel Grave, Grave, North Brabant, The Netherlands":"Grave, Noord-Brabant, Madalmaad"},"fi":{"ca 1314–between 1369 and 1370":"1314–vuodesta 1369 vuoteen 1370","1312–1356":"1312–1356","1333–1391":"1333–1391","1314–1370":"1314–1370","1314":"1314","1356":"1356","1312":"1312","1333":"1333","about 17 August 1356":"noin 17. elokuuta 1356","1370":"1370","1391":"1391","between 1369 and 1370":"vuodesta 1369 vuoteen 1370","ca 1314":"1314","Noord-Brabant, Nederland":"Noord-Brabant, Alankomaat","North Brabant, Netherlands":"Noord-Brabant, Alankomaat","Kasteel Grave, Grave, North Brabant, The Netherlands":"Grave, Noord-Brabant, Alankomaat"},"fr":{"ca 1314–between 1369 and 1370":"1314–du 1369 au 1370","1312–1356":"1312–1356","1333–1391":"1333–1391","1314–1370":"1314–1370","1314":"1314","1356":"1356","1312":"1312","1333":"1333","about 17 August 1356":"environ 17 août 1356","1370":"1370","1391":"1